   A state judge in New York temporarily barred St. Martin's
Press from selling a book about the Israeli intelligence
service, the Mossad.
   State Supreme Court Justice Michael J. Dontzin signed the
order early yesterday morning after lawyers for the Israeli
government argued that publication of the book would endanger
lives and disclose confidential in formation.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Justice Dontzin ordered the New York publishing house to
recall approximately 18,000 copies of the book that have
already been shipped. And St. Martin's said an additional
30,000 orders are being withheld from distribution as a
result of the judge's order.
   The book, "By Way of Deception: The Making and Unmaking of
a Mossad Officer," was written by Victor Ostrovsky. Mr.
Ostrovsky, who now lives in Canada, claims he spent two years
as a Mossad agent. He wrote the book in collaboration with
Claire Hoy, a Canadian journalist.
   A Canadian court last week barred the book's Canadian
publisher, Stoddart Publishing Co. of Toronto, from
continuing production or releasing the book before Sept. 17,
when a hearing is expected to be held, a spokeswoman for
Stoddart said.
   Roy Gainsburg, president of St. Martin's, said he believed
this was the first time that a foreign government had
successfully enjoined publication of a book in the U.S.
   Jonathan J. Lerner, a lawyer representing the Israeli
government, said the book's author had violated a
confidentiality agreement not to divulge any secrets. "If a
CIA agent were seeking to publish vital U.S. secrets in
Israel, wouldn't we expect the Israeli courts to protect
those secrets?" said Mr. Lerner, a lawyer with the New York
firm Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &amp; Flom.
   First Amendment lawyers said courts won't restrain the
publication of a book except in extraordinary situations.
These experts said the Israeli government's fears that the
book might endanger lives may have persuaded the judge to
issue the order.
   But P. Cameron DeVore, a First Amendment lawyer with the
Seattle firm Davis Wright Tremaine, said the U.S. Supreme
Court has held that such orders are unconstitutional unless
an immediate and direct threat to U.S. security -- not that
of a foreign government -- exists.
   "Even if this book is published, as I think it will be,
it's a setback that a restraint order was entered at all,"
said Floyd Abrams of the New York firm Cahill, Gordon &amp;
Reindel, a First Amendment expert.
   Israeli media reports indicated the book contains
allegations that the Mossad knew in advance about the
terrorist attack that killed 240 U.S. Marines in Beirut in
1983 and also includes information about Mossad espionage
activity inside the U.S.
   Justice Dontzin has scheduled a hearing for tomorrow to
review evidence to determine whether the ban should be
continued. But the appellate court is expected to consider
today St. Martin's request that the order be overturned
immediately.
