   FTC INVESTIGATES recruiting by law firms.
   The Federal Trade Commission is looking into whether major
law firms are violating antitrust laws by cooperating with
each other in their recruiting and hiring of law students.
   The investigation, believed to be the first of its kind,
focuses on agreements among big law firms to limit expenses
related to recruiting, such as airline tickets, hotel
accommodations and restaurant meals, according to people
familiar with the inquiry.
   The FTC has targeted law firms based in Cleveland. It
isn't known how many firms are under scrutiny or whether
firms from other cities also are involved.
   In the annual competition for top graduating law students,
large firms routinely coordinate and share expenses
associated with interviewing and wooing potential associates.
The FTC apparently believes that such coordination may
include illegal collusion to limit costs and restrain
competition for sought-after recruits.
   Without "confirming or denying" any specific
investigation, FTC official Michael McNeely said that "if the
firms agree on the level of wining and dining people," they
may be violating federal antitrust laws.
   Employees with three Cleveland firms -- Arter &amp; Hadden,
Baker &amp; Hostetler and Squire, Sanders &amp; Dempsey -- confirmed
that they were under investigation. Another firm under
scrutiny is Jones, Day, Reavis &amp; Pogue, according to people
familiar with the FTC action. The FTC's investigation was
first reported this week by Legal Times, a Washington trade
paper.
   If the commission determines that antitrust laws have been
violated, it could seek to impose fines on the law firms and
request a court order barring anti-competitive recruiting
practices.
   Arter &amp; Hadden's managing partner, Robert Glaser, called
the investigation "ludicrous" and denied any wrongdoing by
his firm or the others under scrutiny.
   Mr. Glaser acknowledged that law firms coordinate student
interview trips, and that this cooperation saves costs for
the firms. But he insisted that coordination takes place
primarily for students' benefit and only when requested by
students. "We aren't limiting our recruiting," he said. "We
aren't colluding on who we invite. We hire independently."
   Employees with Baker &amp; Hostetler and Squire Sanders
confirmed that the firms are being investigated but declined
to elaborate. An employee with Jones Day said the firm's
managing partner, Richard Pogue, wasn't available to comment.
