   INVESTORS SUING DREXEL seek relief from court stay.
   The judge overseeing Drexel Burnham Lambert Group Inc.'s
bankruptcy case has been asked to allow six lawsuits to go
forward accusing Drexel, its former junk-bond chief Michael
Milken and others of a massive conspiracy to rig the
junk-bond market.
   The federal and state civil lawsuits are class actions
filed by investors who allege an intertwined scheme of
securities-law violations, racketeering and other wrongdoing.
In the alleged scheme, sometimes referred to as a daisy
chain, Mr. Milken, Drexel and several corporate raiders are
accused of creating a false market for the securities through
sham transactions and price manipulation.
   Some of the suits also blame the alleged scheme for
exacerbating the crisis in the savings and loan industry.
Federal regulators and Congress have begun their own
investigations into possible criminal activity in the alleged
scheme.
   Although trial dates have already been set for some of the
lawsuits, the cases can't go forward because of an automatic
stay that goes into effect when a company files for
bankruptcy-law protection. Drexel filed under Chapter 11 of
the federal Bankruptcy Code on Feb. 13.
   "The public interest demands that there be a full public
airing and fair prosecution of all civil claims relating to
Drexel's notorious operations, and that the bankruptcy laws
not be used as an offensive weapon to shield the responsible
wrongdoers," the plaintiffs said in a motion filed in federal
bankruptcy court in Manhattan. The motion was filed by
Milberg Weiss Bershad Specthrie &amp; Lerach, which represents
the securities class-action group.
   The motion argues that it will be impossible for Drexel to
come up with a feasible bankruptcy reorganization plan
without getting a better handle on the damages it will face
from the litigation. U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Howard
Buschman III set a hearing for Oct. 2 on the request.
   A spokesman for Drexel said the company will file its
response to the motion later this month. He said, "The reason
for a stay in bankruptcy proceedings is, among other things,
to allow the debtor to develop a comprehensive plan in an
organized way without the need to attend to a multitude of
separate claims."
   Under the plaintiffs' proposal, the court would allow the
cases to continue until damages, if any, are determined, but
it wouldn't allow the plaintiffs to try to collect the money.
