   FORMER HUGHES AIRCRAFT employee wins whistle-blower suit.
   A state Superior Court jury in Los Angeles awarded $1.95
million to a former Hughes Aircraft Co. employee who
contended he was fired after accusing the company of
overcharging the government on defense contracts.
   After five days of deliberations, the jury upheld claims
made by Bobby Coffey, 55 years old, who had worked at Hughes
for more than two decades. As a program-cost analyst at
Hughes's missile division, Mr. Coffey pointed out allegedly
fraudulent practices in which the company overcharged the
government for labor and materials. Melanie Lomax, Mr.
Coffey's attorney, alleged yesterday that the overcharging
amounted to "hundreds of thousands, if not millions" of
dollars.
   Mr. Coffey also claimed age discrimination, but the jury
didn't uphold that particular claim, said Hughes, a unit of
General Motors Corp.
   The company, which is planning to appeal, has denied that
it ever overcharged the government and maintains that Mr.
Coffey was dismissed because he had falsified a time card.
"We feel the verdict was not consistent with the evidence
that was presented," said a spokesman for Hughes.
   ---
   FORMER TAKEOVER LAWYER at Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &amp;
Flom pleaded guilty to three insider-trading counts. Steven
Glauberman, a former Skadden Arps associate, pleaded guilty
to two counts of disclosing confidential information that he
learned at the firm and one count of trading on such
information. Judge Miriam Goldman Cedarbaum in federal court
in Manhattan set sentencing for Dec. 21. Mr. Glauberman is
cooperating with prosecutors in the case, in which three
other defendants have been named.
